  ## Metrics
  ###Upgradeability
  ###Reusability
  ###Reusability Potential
  ###Premature Recycling 
  ###Obsolescence of a model
]
.right-column[
<img src="./imgs/dell-latitude-e6440-off.jpg" alt="drawing" width="80" align="right" style="padding-left: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px;padding-top: 0px;padding-right: 0px"/>
##Obsolescence of a model
***
###Indicates the dificulty of using a device which, even having good performance, is in low utilization.
   
>**O: Obsolescence of a model M**    
>O(M) = The maximum difference between the low.red[*] _usage rate_ threshold and the top _usage rate_ with same Performance
   

```remark
I have to discard my laptop model X with value of use 3, it 
have a _usage rate_ of 30%, instead, users of the Y model with 
the same Value of Use have a *usage rate* by 80%. 
The obsolescence of my X model is at least of 50% (80%-30%).
```
    
[comment]: <> (ccc)

]
.footnotetext[**Note**: .red[*] We define a low _usage rate_ threshold as around 30%. A model should become obsolete because its performance is low and not for other reasons; if in a model we find a set of devices that still have performance to be in use, but are discarded, it means that there is some kind of obsolescence that is not a function of the performance of the model. For example: impossibility to upgrade it, repair it, use it with other software, etc ...]

